Here's my analysis and proposed fix plan for issue #504.

## Problem

When a user adds a custom OpenAI-compatible provider and specifies an exact model, `fire_discoveries()` still fires a `/v1/models` HTTP request. The check at line 1566 of `crates/providers/src/lib.rs`:

```rust
if should_fetch_models(config, name) {
```

only checks `ProviderEntry.fetch_models` (which defaults to `true`). It **never checks whether the user already configured explicit models** in `entry.models`.

Compare with built-in OpenAI-compat providers (line 1530-1533) which have a `skip_discovery` guard — custom providers have no equivalent.

## Fix Plan

**File: `crates/providers/src/lib.rs`**

In the custom providers section of `fire_discoveries()` (lines 1551-1572), add a check: if the provider already has explicit models configured, skip discovery.

```rust
// ── Custom providers ─────────────────────────────────────────────
for (name, entry) in &config.providers {
    if !name.starts_with("custom-") || !entry.enabled {
        continue;
    }
    // ... api_key / base_url guards ...

    // Skip discovery when the user has already specified explicit models.
    let has_explicit_models = !configured_models_for_provider(config, name).is_empty();
    if !has_explicit_models && should_fetch_models(config, name) {
        pending.push((
            name.clone(),
            openai::start_model_discovery(api_key.clone(), base_url.clone()),
        ));
    }
}
```

This means:
- User specifies a model during setup → `entry.models` is populated → no `/v1/models` call
- User adds provider without specifying a model → discovery fires as before
- User can still opt out entirely via `fetch_models: false` in config

**Test: `crates/providers/src/lib.rs` (in the existing test module)**

Add a test that configures a custom provider with explicit models and verifies no discovery is attempted (i.e., `prefetched` is empty but the provider still registers the explicit model). Something like:

```rust
#[test]
fn custom_provider_with_explicit_models_skips_discovery() {
    // Build a ProvidersConfig with a custom provider that has explicit models
    // Call fire_discoveries() and verify the pending list does NOT contain
    // an entry for that custom provider.
    // Then verify register_custom_providers() still registers the explicit model
    // even without discovery results.
}
```

The `register_custom_providers` path already handles this correctly — `merge_preferred_and_discovered_models` will use the preferred models when discovered is empty. So the fix is purely in the discovery-firing logic.

Want me to implement this?

